        "header": "1Introduction",
        "images": [
            {
                "img": "https://arxiv.org/html/2605.06527/2605.06527v1/figures/IC.png",
                "caption": "Figure 1:Overview of the implicit conflict setting.\nUser-assistant dialogues are temporally sparse, and each session provides only partial observations of the user’s evolving circumstances.\nThese observations point to an underlying latent user state, which is not directly observable and must be inferred from scattered conversational evidence.\nImplicit conflicts arise when later observations update the latent state and thereby invalidate earlier memories, either through co-referential conflict or propagated conflict.\nA robust memory system should therefore infer, reason over, and update a coherent representation of the user, and its behavior is evaluated through three forms of state probing.",
                "position": 541
            }
        ]
